<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-627-106  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 627 106.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 10 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Nynex offers backup protection for optical fiber.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   NYNEX Corp. (services).andO;Ticker:    NYN.andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsFiber OpticsPlanningDisaster Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NYNEX OFFERS BACKUP PROTECTION FOR OPTICAL FIBER BOSTON, MASSACHUSETTS,U.S.A., 1990 MAY 7 (NB) -- Following ATandamp;T's network problems earlier thisyear and the continuing risk posed with fiber optic cable, namely thatsomeone will cut it accidentally, NYNEX announced it will provide alternaterouting of its Superpath optical fiber lines serving more than 100 buildingsin Boston and Manhattan.andM;The company also plans to extend the service to many more buildings in thecoming months to protect against service disruptions from cable damage.andP;  BothNew England Telephone and New York Telephone have been equipping their 1.5and 45 megabit-per-second data lines in downtown Boston and New York Citywith backup lines.andP;  The lines, which will be activated over the next severalmonths, have been diversely routed from the companies' central offices toprovide continuous service in the event of a cable cut or other failure.andO;Later this year, the companies will also offer optional access to a secondtelephone central office to maintain service in the event of a problemoccurring in a customer's primary central office.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900508/Press Contact: John Johnson, New EnglandTelephone, 617-743-3433; Tom Pica of New York Telephone, 212-395-0500)</TEXT></DOC>